This gives each species different biological behavior.
I chose this because oral bacteria do not all grow or attach the same way.
This allowed the model to represent:
early colonizers,
secondary colonizers,
disease-associated species.

13. Python CSV export algorithm

flat = biofilm[:, s, :, :].reshape(n_steps_saved, gs * gs)

for cell in range(gs * gs):
    all_data[f"{species}_cell_{cell}"] = flat[:, cell]
df_out = pd.DataFrame(all_data)
df_out.to_csv("multispecies_biofilm_timesteps.csv")

This converts 3D simulation data into a CSV table.
Rows represent timesteps.
Columns represent species-specific grid cells.
I chose CSV export because it lets Python send simulation data into Blender.

14. Blender flattened-grid reconstruction algorithm

row = idx // GRID_SIZE
col = idx % GRID_SIZE

Python saves the 50 × 50 grid as 2500 CSV columns.
Blender uses this code to rebuild the original grid shape.
I chose this because it allows a flat CSV file to become a spatial 3D biofilm again.

15. Blender biofilm keyframe animation algorithm

cube.scale.z = max(0.001, density * BIOFILM_Z)
cube.keyframe_insert(
    data_path="scale",
    index=2,
    frame=frame
)

This changes cube height based on biofilm density.
Low density creates short cubes.
High density creates taller cubes.
I chose this because it visually transforms numerical biofilm density into a 3D growing structure.

16. Blender bacterial movement algorithm

x = ts_values[b * 3] * 5
y = ts_values[b * 3 + 1] * 5
z = ts_values[b * 3 + 2] * 5 + z_offset
sphere.location = (x, y, z)
sphere.keyframe_insert(data_path="location", frame=frame)

This reads bacterial x, y, z coordinates from movement CSV files.
Each bacterium becomes a moving sphere.
I chose this because it turns Python simulation trajectories into visible 3D bacterial movement.

17. Blender competition bar algorithm
height = (row_vals[s] / max_val) * MAX_BAR_HEIGHT

bar.scale.z = max(0.001, height)
bar.location.z = height / 2
bar.keyframe_insert(data_path="scale", index=2, frame=frame)
bar.keyframe_insert(data_path="location", index=2, frame=frame)

This converts population values into animated bar heights.
Larger population means taller bar.
I chose this because it makes species competition visible alongside the 3D biofilm scene.

18. Cross-platform CSV transition algorithm

RStudio curated dataset
→ oral_abundance.csv / oral_metadata.csv
→ PyCharm simulation models
→ biofilm and trajectory CSV files
→ Blender 3D animation

This is one of the most important algorithms in my whole project.
CSV files allow different tools to communicate.
I chose this approach because RStudio, PyCharm, and Blender are not naturally connected.
CSV conversion made it possible to combine:
biological data analysis,
computational simulation,
and 3D visualization.
